{"paperId": "ba2a423d8c7ae6cfa3424fb13bdbe3a35e5f2273", "title": "Unsupervised Evaluation of Interactive Dialog with DialoGPT", "abstract": "It is important to define meaningful and interpretable automatic evaluation metrics for open-domain dialog research. Standard language generation metrics have been shown to be ineffective for dialog. This paper introduces the FED metric (fine-grained evaluation of dialog), an automatic evaluation metric which uses DialoGPT, without any fine-tuning or supervision. It also introduces the FED dataset which is constructed by annotating a set of human-system and human-human conversations with eighteen fine-grained dialog qualities. The FED metric (1) does not rely on a ground-truth response, (2) does not require training data and (3) measures fine-grained dialog qualities at both the turn and whole dialog levels. FED attains moderate to strong correlation with human judgement at both levels.", "venue": "SIGDIAL Conferences", "year": 2020, "citationCount": 143, "influentialCitationCount": 43, "openAccessPdf": {"url": "https://aclanthology.org/2020.sigdial-1.28.pdf", "status": "HYBRID"}, "tldr": {"model": "tldr@v2.0.0", "text": "The FED metric (fine-grained evaluation of dialog), an automatic evaluation metric which uses DialoGPT, without any fine-tuning or supervision is introduced, which attains moderate to strong correlation with human judgement at both levels."}, "embedding": {"model": "specter_v2", "vector": [-0.5353191494941711, 0.9238260388374329, 0.07369976490736008, -0.3730910122394562, -0.5863401889801025, -1.0909863710403442, 1.2064374685287476, 0.031267549842596054, -0.15228413045406342, -0.03143630176782608, 0.7206107378005981, -0.2850993275642395, 0.06616412103176117, 0.2533748149871826, 0.35030949115753174, 0.16178438067436218, -0.6538612842559814, 0.7589130997657776, -0.5157886147499084, -0.6273420453071594, -0.3720339834690094, -0.9802136421203613, -0.19756655395030975, 0.12169650942087173, 0.4564482569694519, 0.19296